tions. Optogenetic activation of M2 axons in STN leads the animal to stop prematurely. By imaging M2 neurons projecting to STN, we find neurons that are active at the onset of stops when executed at the landmark but not when executed spontaneously elsewhere. Our results suggest that the M2-STN pathway can be recruited during visually-guided locomotion to rapidly and precisely control the mesencephalic locomotor region (MLR) through the basal ganglia. By capturing the physiological dynamics through a feedback control model and analyzing neuronal signals in M2, MLR and STN, we find that the cortico-subthalamic projections potentially control MLR activity by differentiating an M2 error signal to ensure fast input-output dynamics.</p></abstract><custom-meta-wrap>
